  "market_context": "ES and NQ both display a 15-minute bearish fair value gap at approximately the same time. Price retraces back up into the fair value gap zones on both correlated indices, providing an opportunity to compare reactions inside the inefficiency.",
  "key_observation": "ES traded back above the high that created the 15-minute fair value gap while NQ failed to reach above its corresponding high, forming an SMT divergence inside the fair value gap itself without needing to drop to a lower time frame.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Mark out the same 15-minute fair value gap on both ES and NQ.",
    "Step 2: Observe price retracing back up into the fair value gaps and note that ES reaches above the high forming the gap while NQ does not.",
    "Step 3: Apply internal range liquidity logic — the fair value gap is defined by a low and a high, so trading above the gap-defining high on one asset but not the other constitutes an SMT divergence.",
    "Step 4: Wait for the reaction; price reverses lower from inside the fair value gap, confirming the SMT.",
    "Step 5: Verify on the 1-minute chart that ES took out the relevant high while NQ failed, showing this is effectively a lower-time-frame SMT visible on the 15-minute."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price reacted lower from the fair value gap after the SMT formed, confirming the divergence as a valid reversal signal.",
  "lessons": "Spotting an SMT within a higher-time-frame fair value gap or PD array effectively captures lower-time-frame SMT divergences without having to drop down — the gap's defining high/low acts as the comparison liquidity point between correlated assets.",
